text: Ok rant time: look I've never liked the chucky series...but this remake seems worse than the other chucky movies and here's why. First off why would you make the kid older, in child's play (original) the kid was young enough to not really see anything wrong with chucky talking to him, the mom was supposed to be the one who tries to see what this doll really is. I didn't like the movie but I can agree that the story sounds much better. Since the kid is older and we already see him trying to find ways to stop chucky, it creates less fear of how long it would take until somebody notices something is wrong with chucky. Then there's that whole "we gotta work together to fight chucky". Ok producer of IT let me tell you something...THIS ISN'T IT!!! THIS IS A SIMPLE STORY ABOUT A KID TOO OBLIVIOUS TO SEE WHAT A DOLL IS DOING!!! Also I'm sorry but I cannot get used to that new look. I can get used to the new joker look, but not the new chucky look! I'm no where near excited for this movie and I hope it fucking burns

text: Eh.  I'm not going to say this looks HORRIBLE or anything. But I am going to say that for the things this seems to do right, it does just as many things wrong. I love the idea of updating this to the modern day commentary about so many "toys" and gadgets these days controlling our lives and everything around us too much. And Hamil seems to be doing a pretty good Chucky impression. He sounds a lot like Brad Dourif. And the cinematography and violence of the movie both look very good. But Chucky's new design is terrible, this version of Andy looks really annoying, and the acting seems really bad. Overall, this doesn't look that impressive.

text: "childs play 2"  star Christine Elise says:  "I think it's an unbelievably huge d*ck move. I think it's a d*uche move absolutely. I don't know why they would f*ck with a healthy franchise. To make a competing franchise with an existing, and like you said healthy, robust franchise is super d*uchey. And nobody from the original franchise is involved; they're not gonna have Brad Dourif, they're not gonna have Don, and they're not gonna have any of us."  "I think the doll is going to be an artificial intelligence doll that goes haywire, so it's not going to have the whole element of the serial killer possessing it, et cetera, so it's not going to be, really, a Chucky film. So, I don't know why they're just taking the title and stealing it and mucking up the waters."  "It's especially d*uchey when you know that Don is developing a TV series and going back to using the title Child's Play; not Bride of, Seed of, Curse of, Cult of Chucky, it's going back to the Child's Play name and it's deep into development. So, this MGM project could have, it hasn't, but it could have, really, easily derailed the TV show project, which would be devastating, because fingers crossed it happens and fingers crossed I'm involved in it, as much as I would like to be. It's an opportunity here where Don can further a story he's been telling for 30 years, but rather than tell it in 90-minute segments every three years or more, he can tell 10 hours of story in 10 weeks, he can get that much more story ahead. And if you've seen Cult and you see how Cult ends, you know how rich in story it is, there's so many doors open now, and to so insensitively threaten the Don Mancini empire I think, is fucked up."   AGREE 100%

text: The  original creators of the franchise are still making stuff for the original continuity and didn't want this to be made. The studio making this is only doing it to make some cash by piggy banking off of the original creator's success. Kinda shitty to the original creators. It'd be one thing if the original continuity wasn't still going and nothing has been done with the Child's Play franchise in a long time but that's not the case. It's a shame too cus it looks like the movie could be fun. I would have personally preferred it if they just made it a completely new doll with a new name, and with a kid not named Andy. So then it'd be a movie with the killer doll concept, while at the same time not as blatantly trying to erase the original continuity since it hasn't ended yet. That's my 2 cents.

text: I always loved the name and aesthetics of Orion Pictures logo; It brings back some good memories of some good films, as well.  That being said, I'm doubtful they'll be able to recapture the company's former glory; perhaps in profit, but not in terms of significantly original IP's.   The frequency of remakes these days is ridiculous. I've it said before, and I'll say it again. It seems to me that the reason why so many remakes are being released, so frequently, is because Hollywood is running out of, or is already out of, significantly original concepts. At the very least, it's consistent with that.

text: Several things. First off, this looks like it could be an¬†entertaining film. The voice sounds very close to Brad Dourif's, which is great as a homage you might say, but I like that it's something new. I don't mind the change in Chucky's look either. I know that when I was a kid, I absolutely loved¬†my two Tekstas, my Poochie,¬†my two Furbies, as well as my green Ooglie and a whole host of techy, gadget, gizmo type toys, so the design for the Buddi doll is very appealing to me. However, the idea of a robot acting up is far less ghoulish than say the spirit of a dead murderer taking up residence in a child's toy and eerily sneaking round the house at night. So because of that, I don't¬†believe it's going to feel as menacing as the Good Guy in the original Child's Play. I think Child's Play should have been a stand-alone film, and yeah sure, there is some entertainment value in the films that followed, but the original had a look and a feel that couldn't be topped. So while I think that this new film has potential to stand out amongst the rest, and try something new with the material it has been given, I just don't reckon it has the story to succeed in being chilling. Then again, the original Child's Play holds a special place in my heart for several reasons, so perhaps I'm Bias.

text: Okay, I'm going to set my honest opinion on this; I used to be VERY terrified of the original Child's Play series, and I sort of still am, but not as much since I sort of got obsessed with it. I like the original idea of a serial killer possessing a doll and becoming the most notorious serial killer of all time, but I honestly think that I will absolutely LOVE this movie more than the original due to how Chucky is programmed. Not just by design (I know he doesn't look like a doll as much as the original movies, but I'm astonished by the way he looks now), but on how the doll works in the movie. In my opinion, it just makes him even more terrifying than the original. But also because of how people are treating technology these days.  Charles Lee Ray or not, I'm pretty sure I will enjoy what will come for this reboot.

text: this movie isn't for 25 to 60 year old... It's for the new generation that wont see movies created before the year 2000. They are missing a lot, but that's what they do. So, how do you keep a legacy of awesome ideas alive... is it called a reboot.... That's what they did in the 70's and 80's, rebooting the 20's and 50's. Difference being, there wasn't 50 million ppl screaming "I Hate Reboots" thinking everything is better in the nostalgic obscured minds. The things you grew up with... not always was really good and probably were panned as terrible by critics, but you like it cuz you grew up with it scaring you... Now, you have become the old critic that isn't impressed, but the kid watching it for the first time, this may be their nostalgic movie that gave them a fear of dolls.  Ask yourself why would you want to take that away from the younger generation?

text: I don't like the idea of Chucky being a rouge A.I. any more than I'd like him being a midget in disguise or some new species of ape. The fact that Chucky was supernatural is what made him scary; he could do what shouldn't be possible and survive when he had no right to because magic was involved, so it was hard to predict what might actually beat him. This premise changes the very core of what Chucky is - it's not about the doll and the evil soul inside anymore, but all the technology around us, with the doll being just one threat among many...arguably one of the lesser threats, at that. And as a more realistic & grounded enemy, it's much easier to imagine scenarios where it could easily be defeated (e.g. have an adult sit on it - expensive toy broken, movie over).   As I wrote this, it dawned on me how natural it felt to refer to the old Chucky as "he" and the new Chucky as "it"; without even thinking about it, I got the impression that the villain isn't a person anymore, but a thing. It'd be like if they reboot Nightmare on Elm Street, but this time Freddy is F.R.E.D.D.I., a malfunctioning dream-controlling machine that was supposed to help people get better sleep. Not necessarily a bad premise, but a completely different movie altogether...just like this one appears to be.   But I guess we'll just have to wait and see, won't we?

text: The thing is Voodoo doesn't have the limitation that Wifi does. I'm not a scientist and I am aware of how suspension of disbelief works, and I DO want to like this movie, however, Chucky as a Wifi virus is broken on a fundamental level. Okay, so you could make a doll that maybe has a Siri like function, maybe it can connect to Spotify or something, but why would a children's toy need to have the functionality of an Amazon alexa? Why would a little child doll be able to control network throughout the entire household? You really want lil' billy altering your digital thermostat? This is not a product that would ever exist.  Then there's the virus aspect. Sure they could stream a sinister voice through it, control it for malicious intent, whatnot, but would the doll come with the physical capability to grasp a knife? Wifi can't program that strength into it.  Plus it's shot with that blatantly obvious horror look of 2010s horror films. I like to be caught off-guard. It won't work.

text: While Mark Hamill is obviously the best choice for this role, and no doubt he'll be great, the movie itself seems to have some... issues.¬†    Biggest thing: The original Child's Play really only worked because Andy was 6. The fact that nobody believes him about Chucky, the fact that he doesn't get institutionalized (immediately), and how he can be manipulated and threatened by Chucky all makes sense from the context that he's a child. Gabriel Bateman is 13.First, who bought him a doll? Second, I got news, bodies start piling up and a teenager starts screaming about killer Cabbage Patch Kids, he's the first one thrown in a hole. And what 13-year-old is afraid of a doll. Pick that thing up and dump it in the compactor. Problem solved.   While I would complain about the 'Small Soldiers'-esque plot of making advanced AI robots into children's toys and allowing them access to relatively advanced technology, who am I kidding? I'm sure they already do that. Moving on.   If Chucky is now a robot and can control all these drones and cars and other tech, what's the point (heh) of the knife? Seriously. I mean, yeah, it's iconic to the franchise, but it originally stemmed from Charles Lee Ray's sadistic personality, and the obvious limitations of his cotton-stuffed body. This new Chucky can apparently possess all manner of other robots to do his bidding, so isn't tromping about with a knife and various other analog death devices kind of limiting itself? Did the AI watch 'Dark Knight' and decide that it, too, wants to "savor the little emotions"? (That's a Joker reference, kids! Get it? Cause it's Mark Hamill!)    And of course, while I can easily see something like the slightly creepy, but still mostly benign 'Good Guy' toy being marketed to little kids and selling in 1988, I do not - UNDER ANY CIRCUMSTANCES - buy the idea that a non-Chinese bootlegging company in 2019 would invest in that pedo-lookin' design, pack it with AI and wireless connectivity, and expect it to sell. No. No way. No how. Not happening.    But even with all that, Mark Hamill might just be worth the ticket anyway...

text: Want to start by saying, No offence to Anyone looking forward to this movie. My heart goes to you, Enjoy you have the right.   That being said I have to say. The plot ,,,,, uh ... just why is Chuck programmable to run Other devices? ..... why, does not compute. Unless for suspense he's more Threatening because he can control Stuff? It makes no sense at all why you'd want a Childs Toy to be able to control UUUhhh,,,,, all of this. A Car, lights, uh... oven, WHY  Really? I'm pretty sure the Movie will explain at least for the ONE person of Why they Have to have this doll but Come On.   I work in retail, and I've seen gimmicky toys come and go. Aside for the Murderous 'Killer Doll' This IS a Gimmick no one would buy this. There is no need for it. It would just get clearanced and the program to run it would have been discontinued in a few weeks. Now if you want to go with That Idea that would be cool, but they are going to most likely going to go with the 'Everyone has to have this Doll' for the sake of being like the Original.   The original concept was that he was like the Cabbage Patch Kids/ My Buddy Dolls because they were Insanely Popular to the point People were actually Fighting people for them. People now a days didn't know or do they care about the pure Anarchy of that time. If they had done it in the 80's,  with some news footage of the mad rush for the Dolls that might have been something but NO we have to make it a gimmick by throwing in the Whole Bluetooth thing.   I really wish it well, not seeing this going anywhere but on the shelves with all the Other Horror remakes in recent years. Just a 'Meh' to call for it.

text: "Something's wrong with Chucky." I'll tell you what's wrong. This was the only slasher franchise that never had a reboot and, along with Nightmare on Elm Street, the only one faithful to continuity throughout the entire series. Cult of Chucky ends with the ineffable Jennifer Tilly's driving off with Chucky, who is now in the body of Fiona Dourif while Andy Barklay is locked up in a psychiatric hospital with multiple Chucky dolls. There was absolutely no reason in the world for these monkeys to reboot Child's Play! They had a perfectly good series with which to move forward!

text: Oh good he actually talks. But this AI stuff. Mixed feelings. There is a good vid explaining why this remake has different origins from the original Child's Play.  However for those fond of the first three, here is what we are losing in this new Chucky, for those new to it:  The original villain was a cultist murderer and transferred his soul inti a doll. Though the villain, he had the interesting journey and challenge of trying to find a new living person to posess and swap out of the doll with. It was interesting and really built the character. With this new robot version, I fear we are getting something shallow. All I see is a killer AI run amok. But where is the personality? The life? If anyone is new to Child's Play, watch the very first two. Then watch this trailer.

text: This has potential but at the same time it seems to be taking itself way too seriously. The franchise has been a satire of the slasher genre, 'Bride of Chucky' & 'Seed of Chucky' were essentially straight up comedies, mocking the absurdity of most Horror films.   This seems like it'll have a few twists of humor, I can't say it won't just from a 2 minute trailer. Overall though from the looks of it, it feels to have a more serious tone which worries me.   Also, I like the design of Chucky. I see a lot of people upset at how clean cut and smoothed out he looks but it fits the technological edge the story seems to be pushing. He's more robotic than just a toy now, he's just killer AI at this point so the smooth, cute demeanor fits the role.   It also leaves plenty of room for him to be beaten to shit which I'm excited to see.
author: Austin Gosetti

text: True Story - I had a chucky doll about 2ft high and it sat next to my monitor. One evening I'm sitting on my bed watching TV and the chucky doll moves. My heart starts beating faster as I stare at the doll wondering what is going on. I then think I imagined it or the doll simply slipped on the desk surface. Then a few minutes later it moved again and I shot out of the room and told my godfather and he looked in the room and found nothing.   I slept downstairs that night and went out next morning as usual. When I came home I noticed a bonfire in the garden and when I went into the garden I could see my godfather was burning the chucky doll.   I said 'why are you burning it you said you found nothing'. He said 'Something happened while you were out and this has to go now'.  He would never tell me what happened but I was so happy when we moved from that place. Some of you won't believe me but I know what I saw that day and it was enough for us to have to burn it.
author: Mark Quinn

text: I was never a huge fan of the Child's Play series to begin with, but I think this movie would have made  A LOT more sense if it was something like Alexa or Siri with the serial numbers filed off.  Like, why would your toy be able to connect to all your devices?  Phone, sure, it can sing and dance to youtube videos or something.  But your car?  Your...I dunno power tools?  Just...why? And it really is a weirdly angular facial design.  It reminds me more of an old school wooden doll than a shiny new plastic thing.  If there was one thing toy companies learned early on, it's that round, smooth shapes appeal to the senses more positively.  But hey, this is all analysis of a movie reboot no one asked for.  So what do I know.

text: I am actually really dissapointed. I headed into this trailer expecting a lot, I came out with a nothing. The plot is the same from the original, that's good, however I feel the kid is too old to be wanting a doll. The death scenes also seem really pathetic, there was one shot in the trailer that had a lawnmower moving by itself and I assume a dad or father figure to Pugg wrapped in christmas lights, this brings the same feeling as ridiculous death scenes from older movies. One last thing, Chucky looks horrible, he doesn't look like a kid's doll at all. He looks like a collectible porcelain doll, which is not who Chucky is. Altogether, the plot of the movie is amazing but the whole script doesn't work and the special effects on Chucky make the whole movie look dodgy, which is unacceptable in 2019 as we have the technology to do better. Very dissapointed with Lars Klevberg, after his amazing movie ''It'' I expected that this was going to be just as good. It was not. I probably won't watch this movie in theatres and watch it on disc when it comes out.

text: Everyones hating on this it seems, but look at it this way. If youre like me, you saw Childs Play as a kid, and it was terrifying back then. The occult was very taboo and wasnt spoken about to the extent it is today. Things like the illuminati were in its infancy of spreading, and witchcraft seemed farfetched, but still scary for an 8 year old.   An 8 year old these days would be more terrified of a toy doll that resembles something they may actually own than another body snatcher tale. Thats just the truth. Maybe it's not going to give you the same feelings 20 years later, but I bet this will stick with your kids 20 years from now in the same way.

text: OKAY! so I am a true Don Mancini Original Child's Play Fan. I love Child's play 2. was okay with 3. Allowed Bride, and suffered through Seed. Got excited with Curse and was disappointed with Cult. SO I will go into this movie with a new set of eyes. As long as "Chucky" is still written well, I will be okay with the whole AI thing (and not the Gothic Voodoo possession). On its own, it look like a much better Horror film then the crap that usually passes.   Plus I had a My Buddy named Paul in 1990 when i first saw Chucky. So all I hope is that this film is able to bring the same level of terror to a new generation of people that really needs a GOD DAMN GOOD SCARE! IN REAL LIFE! (If you don't know what a MY Buddy is, look it up! and also look up "my pet monster". Cool toys use to be nightmare inducing!!!)

text: Is Hollywood relying on old movies for "new" material? Yes indeed. Is this far from the original plot and story of the original Chucky? Absolutely. But that doesn't mean the movie is complete trash or bad. I saw a comment about his face being "chiseled" and not maintaining his look. Well, the previous iteration was an actual doll. This is an animatronic doll, Not a possessed doll. His face is 'chiseled" because they have an actual animatronic puppet being controlled by three people to do movement and facial expression. According to the commentary, 80% of Chucky in the movie is animatronic and the facial expressions are easier to manipulate and show in real time. I do like the more technological view on this version because it takes something that we use every day without worry and turns it against us. We take our easy access to social media and digital services on a whim and think very little about what is actually going on with each keypress, photo uploaded or a file transfer. To have something that we would normally see as harmless to turn around and attack us when we are so blinded by the illusion of control is something to truly be afraid of. I personally when it comes to movies am more daunted by things that really could happen or have happened. This Chucky is based on modern household technology and advanced tech (which I'm sure is closer than not in reality) that can actually move. I have a harder time believing in the possibility of a possessed doll. I look forward to seeing this film with the different "origin" plot of Chucky. I've seen enough possessed dolls (chucky or not) in my lifetime. - 1989 here.

text: First starting it's not bad, an AI who can connect to everything. I like that it is modernized. But by the end, it didnt look so great. I get it, they are remaking chucky so hes basically the star of the show, but no one is going to make a doll your go to like Alexa. Everyone wants something sleek and super small that can sit on a counter or out of sight. Maybe if they left that idea alone, the trailer would be better. However I do think a movie like this would be great but instead of chucky it could be a demon or ghost manipulating the technology Or a full grown actual robot but either way it shouldn't be chucky. Anyway back to the trailer, it just doesnt get me excited to go out and watch it. There wasnt one clip in watching this that had me interested. The doll doesnt even have a certain look to it. It doesnt look creepy or weird but it also doesnt look good. Honestly it looks like crap but this is all opinion. I definitely will watch this being a horror fan, but I'll wait until it hits DVD. It just doesnt seem worth it to go out of my way to  watch it in a theater. The actor playing Andy seems too old and doesnt have that little innocence about him, so it's hard to care for him when chuck goes after him. The first clip of the mom talking to Andy is not very good acting. She has a straight face and monotone voice. The Christmas lights with the dad? Didnt look scary, it looked more fake feeling really. Idk this trailer just doesnt do it for me. The movie might be great but based solely on this trailer, I'm actually disappointed. The video quality looks great but that's really the only good thing I can say about it right now.

text: The things I see at night are scarier than this. Just last night I beheld a landscape of eternal night, the darkness only lit by one pale orb hanging in a decaying gray sky. An undead horror was walking across a muddy hollow of dead and dying trees, with a running chainsaw that is permanently running and cannot be dulled. I floated over this landscape, just below the treetops. (Roughly 90ft) at a lazy 4 to 5 miles per hour. Once it finally noticed me it ran towards me in a rage, attempting to cut trees near me, so that they might bring me to the ground as they fell.  Suddenly I was ripped to a new locale, far away, yet on the same plane,  then I saw a great lake sized body of water lined with jagged ice sculptures of infernal sharks, of course fiendish sharks swam tirelessly about in it as an icy, endless, fierce wind howled across the top of it. Always in the same direction this wind blew. The landscape was frozen, covered in ice that had never been liquid. The ice sculptures of diabolical sharks randomly exploded, sending sharp ice shards flying everywhere, onto the land, Into the water, and then as quickly as they exploded, a new one would begin to form in it's place.

text: Ok... I get it. While the original Child's Play played off on the old childhood fear of dolls coming to life, this version plays off of the current adult fear of a rogue AI deciding to kill off humans. Sounds good in theory. However, there's just one problem. It's been done before... and to death.   Old Chucky: a doll possessed by the soul of a serial killer who knows how to perform voodoo rituals. New Chucky: The Terminator's weird looking Mini-Me.   Even with Mark Hamill voicing the character, I can't see how this is going to work.

text: Some thoughts based on the trailer alone: (I am going to compare a lot to the older films)   Looks - The doll is not close to being decent when compared to the old Chucky, a sinister smile and red eyes aren't scary in the least compared to the psychopathic look the old one had. This one looks like the pampered son of a millionaire gone crazy with some red eyes, his "cute" to crazy look is so minor it takes away any feeling of dread towards the doll. The old Chucky's transformation in both voice and visual was so huge you feared/loved him for his insanity and creepiness, this one does not give me that feeling. I will, however, give HUGE props for using animatronics and not CGI, I LOVE that they did that! His voice seems by the tiny clip to be similar to the old one, I hope it is.   Story and Direction - Giving it an update by making him into a robot with an app is completely fine and perhaps even a good direction, the age of Andy is too out of place though. I can't justify why someone at his seeming age would want this doll. The clip where the kids are the ones to stop him is a bit cliche, It by all means fits but I'm certain they won't let any of the kids die trying to stop him and that will take away a lot of Chucky's carelessness of whom he kills. I also bet that one of the kids is for some stupid reason a "computer wiz" and uses this skill to mess with Chucky's robotic software to give them an advantage. Chucky has to be unpredictable like the Joker, the second it becomes every new scary movie in recent years it becomes too predictable and thus boring, I hope I'm wrong about all of this.   Kills and Method - The kills teased here looks to be somewhat inventive and in line with the old Chucky, I hope they are and if so kudos for that. The camerawork in the kill scenes also seems to be much like the old films, especially the raised hand with the knife, nostalgia for sure!   Overall I'm expecting to be somewhat disappointed being a big fan of the earlier movies, mostly because I won't be able to see past his looks which will annoy me greatly. I will no matter what see it and hope I'm wrong about my predictions but I will not agree with his looks no matter how good everything else hopefully is. Love that they made a new Chucky movie (even though its a remake), love that they used animatronics over CGI and I applaud all the work and effort they put into this movie, huge props to you all for that! Just please, fix his face with CGI or something before launch or make sure to ruin his face into something good for the (hopefully) next movie to follow.

text: There‚Äôs a difference between a remake and an adaptation.  2018‚Äôs IT was an adaptation, that shouldn‚Äôt have been compared or criticized for the changes the director made. It‚Äôs supposed to be a representation of what the director wanted or envisioned the story to be. It‚Äôs not trying to compete with the original, but rather give a new perspective. Can‚Äôt wait to see the second chapter in theaters üòÜ 2019‚Äôs Child‚Äôs Play... Is a remake. It deserves to be criticized, because you simply can‚Äôt beat the original. Chucky or ‚ÄúBuddi‚Äù looks so ugly, that no one will buy that doll. Instead, we‚Äôll continue buying the Chucky replicas of ‚ÄúBride of Chucky‚Äù, because even his ugly mug is more appealing to look at. Just because we can have more realistic looking CGI, doesn‚Äôt mean we should use it. Did we learn nothing from the Sonic fiasco? I may watch it years from now on Putlocker ü§∑üèΩ‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è... Also, I feel like they know he looks like flaming trash, because you only see one shot of his actual face throughout the trailer. üëèüëèüëèüòí Hollywood needs to find someone else‚Äôs childhood to go fucking ruin and tarnish, instead of rewrapping the 90‚Äôs eras shit and sending it back. The only people excited for this, is normie hype beasts and early 2000‚Äôs kids/preteens who missed out on the 90‚Äôs hype.  They also could‚Äôve fucking asked Brad Dourif to do the voice (no offense to Mark), but... no thanks.  I support adaptations, not remakes.

text: "Something's wrong with Chucky!!" Yeeeeeah, no shit Andy.  The fear and suspense brought upon by the original Child's Play was the juxtaposition of an adorable, unassuming cabbage patch-esc doll who was actually the soul embodiment of a serial killer. The first time seeing Child's Play, you would never have guessed that Andy was telling the truth! Chucky WAS Alive!! We don't even see the Good Guy Doll become "Chucky" until about 40 minutes into the original film.  So Hollywood, tell me; what exactly am I supposed to be shocked or scared of when the Buddi doll looks absolutely terrifying right out the box? Gives me Glen vibes from Seed of Chucky and that's NOT a good thing.  With that being said let's talk about the world building of this film. No kid in their right mind would EVER want a doll that scary! The focus groups and Parent organizations would have it pulled immediately for remodel. Especially, when you take into account that the marketed demographic for any type of doll is girls aged 4-10. Andy looks like he's pushing 16 (definitely not the demographic; no matter how advanced the doll supposedly is). What's this teenage boy still doing playing with dolls? Instead of creepy ass dolls, perhaps the "Kaslan" company should stick to making Thermostats, Cars, Table-saws, and...Lawnmowers? Really??  Why not make some Chrysler Popcorn in your Chrysler Microwave. While you're at it, make a smoothie with your Chrysler Blender and workout to music on your Chrysler Sound System. Before sleeping in your Pressure controlled Chrysler Bed take a nice soothing bath in your Chrysler Bathtub. Get into your Chrysler PJs but don't forget to brush your teeth with your Chrysler Electric Toothbrush and Chrysler Toothpaste. Absolute Bollocks!  I know Don Mancini ran his creation into the ground but damn, I see the franchise is dead no matter whose hands it's in.

text: I love reading the same comment over and over and over again. Each comment less original and more annoying than the last. "Oh wahh, one of  my favorite horror movies is being remade. Woe is me."  Some will love it. Some will hate it...and some will appreciate the opportunity to enjoy another version of a classic. Sit yall's whiny simple minded asses at home so I can go see Child's Play 30 years later...because I assume you simple folks wouldn't dare spend a dime on this. REMAKE! How ridiculous would it be to release the remake using the exact same script as the original while changing nothing. Enjoy the Golden Age of Television and stop ruining something I've been hoping for since they remade Nightmare on Elm Street. Robert Englund will always be classic Freddy, no argument, I wish Freddy was different....I still enjoyed the story in the remake. I enjoyed it. Ugh, everybody thinks they're a movie critic.

There are thousands of talented people with hundreds of original movie ideas that would be great if Hollywood producers funded them but they put their money on remakes and sequels because it‚Äôs safe. It‚Äôs safe because remakes and sequels consistently make money, and that is entirely the audiences fault. If you all want to prove them wrong, go see great original indie films (which there are hundreds of) instead of the garbage you all are criticizing but still probably paying money to see. Doing this will actually start a change in mainstream film where original ideas are funded because they ALSO make money.

text: Here is the synopsis: "Buddi", the bastard child of the Good Guy doll from the original movie, is linked to a computer you utilize through your "smart" phone. Something goes wrong with the technology and the doll named Chucky comes to life, for yet unknown reasons, and wants to kill. In the original movie, Charles Lee Ray (a murderer on death's door) uses a spell to live through a doll. In this poorly conceived Tech version, a doll just comes to life because of a software bug... no interesting background, no serial killer soul, no voodoo... nothing of substance.  The ending seems to be, by the trailer's own admission, a near replica of the director's previous shit remake of Stephen King's "IT", parts 1 and 2. By this I mean the new clich√© "only the children can save us! We adults are too simple-minded to stop a doll! Let the 12-year-olds save the day!" bullshit ending. As with most, if not all, movies made in the last 15-20 years, society is becoming a pathetic excuse for inclusiveness within cinema, and EVERYONE has to have their own movies: Blacks, children, pregnant women, the deaf, blind and the otherwise handicapped. Not to say these people can't have leading rolls, but just don't force the part upon them! Let the narrative explain and control whom is right for the part instead of throwing darts at a board to pick a "minority" star. Overall, there is nothing about this movie I'd enjoy seeing. It is yet another pointless, money-desparate attempt at oversaturating the film market with an already completed, already told story in efforts to lure people to buy their merchandise. There is no reason for this movie to have been made, and I am sorry for Mark Hamill's roll in it, which I believe to be a waste of his talent.

The storyline is a bit different from the first movies (SPOILER AHEAD): No Charles Lee Ray this time, Chucky is no longer a possessed doll trying to turn into a human. Instead, it/he is the result of a en employee's desire for vengeance who decides to mess with the doll's system to remove any form of censure from its program.   This movie might remind you of Stephen King's Christine. I kinda felt bad for Chucky on multiple occasions, actually.

text: LMFAO all the little girls here getting pissed. Just look how ruffled their jimmies are knowing that our era was where it's at, that they will never know it. XD haha  Like I think the 70's might have had it's "highs" amidst the lows like the gas crisis, but I'm not some cry baby child boo hooing because I wasn't there. I mean the 80's weren't always fun, we had Reagan, The Cold War, AIDS crisis, The Satanic Panic, market decline ect... Not so fun.  But with that said it was the greatest time, because if you aren't a child then it was your time. ^^   Now kids have whatever the fuck this boring era is.... Mubble rap and faggot sjws...whooohoo?  They will never experience what we have ;P Not having phones so our mums wouldn't bitch us out, staying out late, raves, Phatt pants, glitter, lasers... FUCKING SURGEEEEE!!!!  Oh and really...really good drugs.  Remember when punk shows were violent? When venue owners were drug dealers and going to the club was all you could do because if it wasn't about music then it wasn't worth your time? I sure do.  One of my favorite memories is sneaking into the theaters with my brother and his friends to see a re-screening of Clive Barker's Night Breed, based on the book Cabal, you know those things made of paper that hold stories? Of course not, you have e-books!! But that's unfair credit, kids are idiots and don't read anymore. But I digress.... Later that night we went to some club called Mot√∂r, they didn't even care I was underage, obviously a child myself. The dj played Shannon's "Let the music play" I remember hearing some Skinny Puppy as well, good times....  If you were born any time in the 2000's then you're an infant to me, absolutely devoid of experience or fun.  85' baby.Young enough to be shown, old enough to know!   Now go put your toys away and wash up for bed time, kiddos. Oh and tell your collective mums that I enjoyed spilling my teen seed for them all those years. :D

text: Honestly, I enjoyed it. I wasnt expecting much, but got more than expected. Some good humor, good kills, some 80s feel during some kills, and good voice acting by Mark Hamill. It of course wasnt your classic Chucky, but it definitely was a good movie. Kept my interest, gave me some laughs. The modern technology that Chucky had with the wifi app and interaction with nearby devices was pretty cool too. Plus Andy could see what Chucky sees through a cell phone via the app. It really wasn't a shit movie at all. I'm a horror fan, and love the classics, so again I wasn't expecting much, but this is not a horrible movie by any means. Take it for what it is, it's a fun movie.

text: I think the most interesting thing is that they have now essentially given Chucky powers. Previously the only reason that Chucky was hard to kill is because he is just a hunk of plastic and thus has no vital organs. I also have the theory that Chucky still has the physical strength that he had in life. A small doll with the strength of an adult man. I get this impression when I watch the fight scenes. But now he is a walking universal remote.    However I am not a fan of Chucky's new face. Simply because it doesn't look like him. I suppose this comes with it being a remake. text: People are slamming the new Chucky's appearance but what they don't get is why it's his scariest attribute. Why? Because then he looks just like a toy so it seems completely believable that the adults would never suspect him. Hell, no one would unless they actually saw him do it first hand. He's so unsuspecting. The original Chucky had to look creepy because HE'S A FUCKING DOLL! WEAK AND PATHETIC! WANNA BEAT THE ORIGINAL, HIT HIM. KICK HIM. RIP HIS HEAD OFF. HE'S A TOY! This Chucky has menace. He has danger. He's more than a possessed talking doll. He can control any electronic device from phones and tvs to YOUR CAR AND LAWN MOWER. He is WAY more powerful AND dangerous than the original. And his innocent, unassuming appearance coupled with this fact makes him terrifying. Because you may suspect the creepy kids doll sat on the shelf or in the attic but you NEVER suspect the innocent looking toy.

text: The worst thing about reboots, are how the fans want literally the same exact thing over and over again. I'm a fan of the old Chucky movies, but they made a joke out of them. In this, Chucky isn't a joke, and has never been creepier. Mark Hamill did amazing in voicing the character. This is the Chucky I've always wanted, one that actually gives you the creeps, and I really enjoyed this rewrite. It wouldn't be as good if it didn't change anything from the original. We still have Mancinis version, and I'm glad to have this version too, and I hope to see more of this Chucky. We needed a straight horror Child's Play, and not the comedy horror, and I enjoyed Chucky having more screen time than he's ever had. I'm glad to have both versions. Sometimes, change isn't bad. If it didn't do anything different, then there would be no sense in even rebooting it.

text: I did enjoy the movie, but it isn't really Child's Play, and not really Chucky for me. Spoilers ahead(?) Mark Hamill did a great job voicing Chucky though, not gonna lie.  It's just that it feels like they named the movie Child's Play just to sell more tickets. It has nothing to do with Child's Play other than the character names are the same, and Chucky got a small makeover.  I loved the movie, but it's just that it bothers me a little bit.

text: They ruined this movie. They took away everything that made this movie charming. It's supposed to be about a doll possessed by a serial killer named Charles Lee Ray. That's where the name "Chucky" comes from... Now it doesn't makes sense why he's called Chucky. The original Child's Play birthed the genre of creepy haunted doll now turning it into some robot doll that got malfunctioned is stupid. It's not a "fresh take" or a "twist" because the robot invasion plot is getting clich√© now. The doll had no personality and wasn't scary at all. And Andy in the original was a charming, sweet boy, now this new Andy is a tech savy brat who doesn't suit to be interested in dolls at all and adding all these random kids in here is lame too. If anyone prefer's this to the original, then people's standards has certainly gotten low over the years. This remake is garbage even without comparing it to the original...

text: I actually thought this was a much better movie in just about every way possible then the original.  It wasn't trying too hard and voodoo is just not scary or a believable origin. This actually attempted to have a heart, for what it's worth it succeeded. The way they created this as an animatronic Alexa was genius. I like how Chucky only learned from actions of other. Sort of a reflection of all their own faults and ignorance . His creepy obsession with Andy was well done by Hamal, along with Chucky's overall demeanor. Programing being hacked by foreign entities and interfering with software. Just about the hole idea plays on our modern technology and it's integration in the modern world.  Also with the fears that associate to that same technology. IMO the best horror movie reboot in a long time.
